abstract: Party leaders who are fatalistic about Democrats’ chances in 2020 are musing about possible late entrants to the race. Sherrod Brown? Michelle Obama?
snippet: Party leaders who are fatalistic about Democrats’ chances in 2020 are musing about possible late entrants to the race. Sherrod Brown? Michelle Obama?
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When a half-dozen Democratic donors gathered at the Whitby Hotel in Manhattan last week, the dinner began with a discussion of which presidential candidates the contributors liked. But as conversations among influential Democrats often go these days, the meeting quickly evolved into a discussion of who was not in the race — but could be lured in.

headline_main: Anxious Democratic Establishment Asks, ‘Is There Anybody Else?’
headline_print_headline: Anxious Democrats Ask, ‘Is There Anybody Else?’

abstract: The candidate of plans needs a really good one right now.
snippet: The candidate of plans needs a really good one right now.
lead_paragraph: On Sunday, Elizabeth Warren said that she would soon release a plan explaining how she intends to pay for “Medicare for all.” Like many policy wonks, I’ll be waiting with bated breath; this could be a make or break moment for her campaign, and possibly for the 2020 election.

abstract: The problem is not just paranoia. It’s also that she questioned a candidate’s motives rather than the soundness of her views.
snippet: The problem is not just paranoia. It’s also that she questioned a candidate’s motives rather than the soundness of her views.
lead_paragraph: On Friday, Hillary Clinton suggested on a podcast that the Russian government might be “grooming” Democratic Representative Tulsi Gabbard of Hawaii as a third-party presidential candidate and referred to the former Green Party candidate Jill Stein as “a Russian asset.”

abstract: The company also announced several new steps to reduce the spread of false information, including an effort to label posts from state-sponsored media.
snippet: The company also announced several new steps to reduce the spread of false information, including an effort to label posts from state-sponsored media.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Facebook said on Monday that it had recently found and taken down four state-backed disinformation campaigns, the latest of dozens that it has identified and removed this year and a sign of how foreign interference online is increasing ahead of the 2020 presidential election.

abstract: The long-awaited proposal breaks from Obama-era Democratic priorities by critiquing charter schools and testing.
snippet: The long-awaited proposal breaks from Obama-era Democratic priorities by critiquing charter schools and testing.
lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts had released dozens of policy plans before tackling K-12 education, making her the last leading Democratic primary contender to do so.

headline_main: Justin Trudeau, Opioid Trial, N.F.L.: Your Monday Briefing

abstract: New research shows that even if wealthy residents move away, the revenue at death from those who stay outweighs any loss in income taxes.
snippet: New research shows that even if wealthy residents move away, the revenue at death from those who stay outweighs any loss in income taxes.
lead_paragraph: Arkansas reaped a windfall when a Walmart founder, James L. Walton, known as Bud, died in 1995 with a fortune estimated by Forbes at $1.65 billion in today’s money. The next year, state estate tax receipts jumped 425 percent, to about $183 million in current dollars.

abstract: Stormy news cycles, and an audience thirsty for political commentary, have changed what works on TV at 11:35 p.m.
snippet: Stormy news cycles, and an audience thirsty for political commentary, have changed what works on TV at 11:35 p.m.
lead_paragraph: The formula for success on the big late-night network television shows used to be simple. Keep it light, keep it moving and book a major star, preferably one in the news.
